MEDIUM|internal/verify/syntaxguard.go:138|extractFencedCode uses fenceRe.FindStringSubmatch and validates ONLY the first markdown fence. A common multi-block LLM response shaped as a non-Go fence (e.g. a text fence) followed by a broken Go fence extracts the first non-Go block, matches nonGoFenceLangs, and returns nil — the broken Go in the second fence is never parsed, a silent false negative.|In extractFencedCode iterate all fences via FindAllStringSubmatch; skip explicitly non-Go tags and validate the first Go-tagged or untagged block (or validate every Go-eligible block and flag if any fails). Add a two-fence test (non-Go first, broken Go second) asserting a non-nil error.|correctness|60|internal/verify/syntaxguard.go:137-143|claude
MEDIUM|internal/verify/syntaxguard.go:30|fenceRe body capture is non-greedy so the first triple-backtick INSIDE the fenced body closes the block. Valid Go containing a triple-backtick string literal is truncated mid-expression, fails to parse, and because hadFence is true the guard flags VALID code as invalid_syntax — the exact false-positive trust degradation the guard exists to avoid.|Require the closing fence on its own line by anchoring the close with (?m) and a leading newline so an inline backtick run mid-line cannot close the block. Add a fixture containing a backtick-bearing Go string literal asserting NoError.|correctness|30|internal/verify/syntaxguard.go:23-30|claude
